+        /* Widescreen extrusion for this board's cloud/proscenium backdrop
+         * ("pillar", mdlId[0]) and floor ("yuka", mdlId[1]); the foreground
+         * prop set (mdlId[2]) stays untouched.
+         *
+         * The floor is a single baked 5x5-vertex plane: one diamond-tile
+         * texture plus a center play-circle decal, both painted into ONE
+         * image (confirmed via a raw HSF dump -- not a repeating tile).
+         * Scaling the whole piece about its center to close the widescreen
+         * gap also enlarges that decal, so instead only the outer ring of
+         * the 5x5 grid is pushed out per axis about the bbox center; the
+         * inner vertices and every UV stay untouched, so the decal and tile
+         * density stay native (mp6_widescreen_extrude_model_border_xz()).
+         *
+         * The floor's shadow texcoord is generated live from this same
+         * vertex buffer (game/hsfdraw.c's GX_TG_POS-driven SetShadow), so
+         * displacing the border ring also drags the projected shadow with
+         * it, and a texture-matrix compensation can't selectively undo a
+         * per-vertex displacement without corrupting the untouched native
+         * vertices too. Fixed by leaving this instance 100% native -- its
+         * shadow stays pixel-accurate over the area the native 4:3 game
+         * actually rendered -- and moving the border-extended visual fill
+         * to a second, non-shadow-casting duplicate of the same asset
+         * (mp6_widescreen_floor_border_fill_dup()). A shadow that would
+         * fall past this instance's native 800x800 footprint is simply
+         * absent there instead of stretched.
+         *
+         * Extending the pillar's own edges sideways to close its gap
+         * initially opened a Z-parallax window: the pillar sits nearer the
+         * camera than the golden-swirl backdrop behind it, so sliding its
+         * edge sideways swept the fixed party camera's view ray across that
+         * real depth gap, revealing the floor/backdrop through it. Several
+         * iterations pushed the pillar's own Z back toward the backdrop's
+         * depth to close this, tuned on-device by scanning for floor-
+         * colored pixels in the gap region across several reference
+         * widths, each cutting the leaked pixel count further.
+         *
+         * That Z-shift-and-split approach was retired in favor of one that
+         * avoids the parallax problem entirely: the pillar's own outermost
+         * native vertices (|x|=800 exactly) are duplicated into the
+         * object's own grown buffers, and only the duplicates translate
+         * outward -- never scaling, so the art stays byte-identical: the
+         * pillar itself never moves or splits, so there is no depth gap to
+         * open. The connecting strip between original and duplicate edge
+         * carries pinned UVs sampled from the source edge loops, continuing
+         * the native flat-white-column / grey-dissolve / gold-trim-arch
+         * texture outward at native texel density with zero stretch
+         * (mp6_widescreen_extend_pillar_edge()). The floor border-fill
+         * duplicate's own border cells also retarget their UVs onto
+         * shadow-free regions of the source texture, so the extended
+         * margins don't smear the baked house/fence shadow that the real
+         * (shadow-receiving) floor still carries untouched
+         * (mp6_ws_floor_dup_clean_sts). */
+        if (i == 0) {
+            mp6_widescreen_extend_pillar_edge(obj->mdlId[i], "pillar");
+        } else if (i == 1) {
+            mp6_widescreen_floor_border_fill_dup(DATA_mdparty + i, "yuka");
+        }
@@ -1864,0 +2141,8 @@
+        /* Tears down the floor's own border-fill duplicate instance
